This is a simple implementation of the login server needed by the
Google Drive KODI Addon at https://github.com/cguZZman/plugin.googledrive

I wrote this because I couldn't get his official server code to compile
(from here https://github.com/cguZZman/drive-login ).

This other one works, but it uses some older javascript libraries and
I didn't want to have to rely on something that's always going out of
date (https://github.com/aldacco/drive-login/ ).

This server's only dependency is OpenSSL. If you've got a C compiler
installed you can build it just by typing "make".

To run it you'll first need to setup your Google OAuth 2.0 credentials,
just like for those other servers. Follow the setup instructions on the
aldacco repo.

After you obtain the credentials, set them in two environment variables

  export GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=..client id..
  export GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=..client secret..

Then run with
  ./kodilogin -h localhost

It listens on port 3000 by default, so you'll need to enable
  http://localhost:3000/callback
as the redirect URI for this Google client. Also you'll have to configure
the GoogleDrive plugin to use http://localhost:3000 as its server.

If you want to run it on a public address, Google will require you to have
a valid DNS name, and it will require https. So you're going to need to get 
your own server certificate and key. Once you have those, you can set them
using -c for the server certificate file and -k for the server private key file.

If you want to bind the listener to a specific address use -a, otherwise
it will listen on all available network interfaces.

So you might invoke as
  ./kodilogin -h www.example.com -p 8000 -c servercert.pem -k serverkey.pem

which would correspond to a server URL of https://www.example.com:8000 and
use https://wwww.example.com:8000/callback as its redirect URI.

-----

I've also added a little helper program called ltunnel. It forwards a port
from the local machine to a port on a remote machine, in cleartext. (I.e.
it's not encrypted at all, like stunnel would be.) It's useful to access a
kodilogin server running on your network, from a box that can't run its own
web browser, such as a CoreElec install.

Since your CoreElec box can't run a web browser, it's no use to run kodilogin
on that box as a localhost server because you can't complete the Google
login process without a web browser. So as a workaround, you can run the
kodilogin as a localhost server on some other PC on your home network -
one that also has a working web browser. Then you run ltunnel on the
CoreElec box, pointing to the PC. Then any connection to localhost:3000
on the CoreElec box actually talks to localhost:3000 on the PC.

Of course, you will need to compile ltunnel for ARM Linux in order to
get a binary that works on the CoreElec box. Then you can enable the
CoreElec SSH server to copy the binary over and run it there.

Assuming your PC was running at IP address 192.168.1.100 with the default
port 3000, you just run on the CoreElec box `ltunnel -h 192.168.1.100` and
leave it running. Then with your Google Drive plugin configured to talk to
http://localhost:3000 it will be using your PC's kodilogin server to
authenticate.
